    <name>In your own words: Describe differentiated instruction</name>
    <intro>&lt;div style="text-align: left;"&gt;In the presentation in Topic 2, we had some fun with words that describe what &lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;&lt;abbr title="Differentiated Instuction"&gt;DI&lt;/abbr&gt; is&lt;/span&gt; and is &lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;not&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;&lt;abbr title="Differentiated Instuction"&gt;DI&lt;/abbr&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;is:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;img title="Differentiated Instruction word cloud" style="width: 282px; height: 212px; margin: 0px;" alt="flexibly-grouped, Dynamic Assessment-driven, Student centered, Multimodal, Responsive" src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/DI_Wordle.JPG" complete="true" width="960" height="720" /&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt; &lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;&lt;abbr title="Differentiated Instuction"&gt;DI&lt;/abbr&gt; is &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold;"&gt;not:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;img title="What Direct Instuction is not" style="width: 280px; height: 209px; margin: 0px;" alt="tracking, instruction, chaos, individulazed, homogenous, grouping louder, slower" src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/Slide6.JPG" complete="true" width="960" height="720" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt; Keep brainstorming ways to describe the new way of planning that DI represents. Here are two analogies to get you started, from &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Supporting Differentiated Instruction: A Professional Learning Communities Approach&lt;/span&gt; by Robin Fogarty and Brain Pete, 2011, Solution Tree Press. Add your thoughts by clicking on the &lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;Edit &lt;/span&gt;tab. Be sure to include your name in parentheses after your addition.&lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt; Differentiation is like a &lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;garden&lt;/span&gt; because both take time to grow and grow at different rates; each has unique needs, and all represent natural beauty.&lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt; Differentiation is like an &lt;span style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;octopus&lt;/span&gt; because both are adaptive, flexible, and reach out to others.&lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt; Below is a collection of analogies. These images were made by using the website &lt;a href="http://www.wordle.net/" title="new wbsite - opens new window" target="_blank"&gt;Wordle&lt;/a&gt;  Try it! It's easy and fun! &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img title="Wordle on DI" style="width: 560px; height: 421px; margin: 0px;" alt="Wordle  showing different phrases - tailored clothes, welcoming, a football team, welcoming, melting pot, a family, improvisational jazz ensemble, let go of the reins and trust the horse" src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/Wordle_on_What_is_DI.jpg" complete="true" /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</intro>
